{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/2016/03/aggregating-google-analytics-browser-statistics-with-r2d2/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"J. Pedro Ribeiro"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"9b1e3a5b-d989-5746-b348-1074c6d51bf1","excerpt":"I love Google Analytics but the browser usage stats always annoyed me. Since modern, evergreen browsers release features very frequently, you end up having toâ€¦","html":"<p>I love <strong>Google Analytics</strong> but the browser usage stats always annoyed me. Since modern, evergreen browsers release features very frequently, you end up having to combine multiple entries into one in order to get a more usable data. For example, when identifying the users on Chrome, I really don't care how many of them are on Chrome 48 vs 49, I only care if they are on Chrome.</p>\n<p>To solve this, I created a small <strong>Node.js</strong> app called <a href=\"https://github.com/jpedroribeiro/r2d2\">Rapid Reporting Device Dashboard</a>, or <a href=\"https://github.com/jpedroribeiro/r2d2\">r2d2</a> for short (yes I really wanted to create an r2d2 acronym).</p>\n<p>It uses the Google Analytics API to connect to your dashboard. Reads the browser stats from the last 30 days and prints out in an <em>aggregated</em> manner. The rules are, of course, very customised to my needs but the code itself is very easy to change if you need a different output.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 403px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/045fd/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 132.91139240506328%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"r2d2\"\n        title=\"r2d2\"\n        src=\"/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/045fd/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/c26ae/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png 158w,\n/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/6bdcf/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png 315w,\n/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/045fd/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png 403w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 403px) 100vw, 403px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>I wrote it using some <strong>ES2015</strong> features like: <code class=\"language-text\">let, const, import</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">template strings</code>. It's all up on <a href=\"https://github.com/jpedroribeiro/r2d2\">GitHub</a> so feel free to have a look.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Aggregating Google Analytics Browser Statistics with r2d2","date":"March 27, 2016"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2016/03/aggregating-google-analytics-browser-statistics-with-r2d2/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2016/03/web-ethics/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Web Ethics","tags":["opinion","ethics"]}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2016/04/web-education/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Web Education","tags":["opinion","education"]}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["63159454","792910177"],"slicesMap":{}}